<br>
Careful years of scriptural study, focus, practiced meditation, and a life of devotional will yield a glimpse into the mind of God, albeit interpreted through a human brain.  <br>
<br>
For the non-book religions, or shamanistic religions, practiced meditation and rituals, as well as some forays into conscious altering drug use can produce experiences with the divine.  The shaman is not a mad-man or schizophrenic who succumbs to chaos under possession, he is a normal man or woman, who has learned to master chaos.  To a certain extent, so is the Catholic priest who has learned to make some sense out of the chaos of his world and the interpretation of his dreams and visions in response to prayer.  <br>
<br>
<br>
For the skeptics, yes, there is a portion of the brain directly related to the religious experience that allows us to have hallucinations or hear 'voices'.  Then again, perhaps it is this part of the brain that ALLOWS us to communicate and experience the divine.  <br>
<br>
