<br>
<br>
First thing I noticed... on two occasions people quoted Karl Marx by saying <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Religion is the opium of the masses.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> I've thought on that matter, ever since a friend of mine tried to get me to join the communist party. (Bleh... that didn't happen.) This notion is a very closed view rooted in contempt for what the Church has evolved into, and really has nothing to do with Religion itself.<br>
<br>
Truth be told, there's nothing really wrong with Religion as Quarken, Brack, etc. put it. To use the Christian religion as an example, it wasn't originally intended to be the bureaucratic bullshit that has been seen in recent centuries (and was what led Martin Luther to post his theses). Over time it has evolved into a business to survive, and this business-like behaviour is what has led to a rise in atheism in western civilization.<br>
<br>
Religion, at least the Christian religion, was originally about bringing the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> teachings</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, not the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> glory</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> of Christ to the world. Fundamentally, Christ's teachings can be summed up in the words <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> do unto others as you would have them do unto you</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. There's more intricacies to it than just that, but basically, there you have it. Treat others with respect and dignity. And that same fundamental concept appears in most of the organized religions that have managed to last more than a few decades. <br>
<br>
Christ was deified as a means for convincing the pagans to accept these civil teachings. &quot;Well you have to accept what he says, because he's, uh, the son of God, and as such he's God himself.&quot; Truth is, he was just a man. A very humble man that had a good idea. The concept of congregation in Christianity arose during the decline of the Roman empire as a means for survival, and for the first few hundred years most Christians were actually relatively nomadic and solitary. This congregation became, over time, what it is now. But getting together with like-minded people to do good work is always a good thing. Whether you do it out of Religion, or out of Compassion is irrelevant. What matters is that you do help others, and treat them with the dignity and respect that they deserve.<br>
<br>
As it appears to me, Atheists don't oppose God, they oppose the Church. They attack God because s/he is representative of the Church. They vehemently, in some cases violently, push for separation between Church and State, because they feel threatened by the power represented by the Church.<br>
<br>
<br>
Now that I've thoroughly pissed some of you off, let me explain myself.<br>
<br>
<br>
I'm an agnostic. I don't mean that as many of you read it. I look through my telescope, and I know that there is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> something</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> out there. It is extremely arrogant to believe that we became of our own will, that we were the first intelligent beings. It is even more arrogant to believe that we are alone in this great creation we know as the Universe. I know within my very being that there is some superior form of life out there that breathed everything into existence. What I'm agnostic on is whether that being is malevolent, indifferent, or benevolent. I lean towards indifference with occasional benevolent interference. I like to believe that we exist as an experiment by some greater being to understand itself. In essence, that existence is within some cosmic petri dish.<br>
<br>
I like to believe that I've come to my conclusions on my own, but I know that I've been deeply influenced by those who have belief to whom I've spoken on the matter. These include my Anglican minister, catholic priests, buddhist monks, Jehovah's Witnesses, and a whole plethora of other religious leaders and adherents. The thing that interests me the most is that of the Leaders, only one of them has expressed any surprise that I did not want to accept it blindly. They all agreed that I absolutely must go through a period of doubt in order to make my mind up and truly believe what is right <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> for me</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
<br>
Yes. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> For me</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. It doesn't matter what religion I follow, so long as it makes sense to me, and teaches concepts that jive with my world view.<br>
<br>
<br>
Now. The atheists are screaming bloody murder. But I don't really care, because I know in my heart that we are not alone, and that is all I need. One of the most popular questions Atheists like to raise is: <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> if God created heaven and earth, then who created God?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
To this, the best answer I can offer was given to me by one of the JW's that visits our house every Saturday. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Nobody. God just <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> is</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> And the more I look through my Telescope, the more I have to agree. It's a wonderful creation, this universe in which we live, and it has to have come from somewhere.<br>
<br>
To quote one of my favourite movies, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> truth is, no religion's got it right. It doesn't matter what you believe in, what matters is that you have an idea.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<br>
Who knows. Maybe I'll turn into an existentialist and decide that I don't exist when my eyes are closed. I've gone through a dozen or more theories about the fundamentals of why I'm here, and I expect to go through dozens more, if not hundreds, in the 80 or so more years I plan on living. My view is constantly changing as new experiences, and new ideas enter into my own personal &quot;theory of everything.&quot;<br>
<br>
I have a lot of respect for people who have gone through the same soul searching that I am now, and very little respect for people that blindly follow a particular religion without any proof for themself. One of the points in bold above is the doubt. You must go through a period of doubt and soul searching to attain clarity, and to decide which collection of ideas is best <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> for you</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. You could also find yourself in exactly the same situation I am, coming up with your own set of ideas. Perhaps some day I'll write a book, but not until I've figured things out to my own satisfaction. I doubt I ever will figure things out, but that has become my meaning of life.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Now, I trust that you'll show the same intelligence you've shown above, and realize that I need to write these words not out of an effort to convince you that you're all wrong, but out of an effort to understand the jumble of thoughts that goes on inside my head. I don't know what's right, and I'm not going to oppose anybody who believes something, so long as they believe for the right reasons. Truth be told, I welcome people who look at my little theory and tell me what's wrong with it, because it gives me a new perspective on myself, and the opportunity to better figure out my universe.<br>
<br>
<br>
Be well. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ugonuso.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gonuso</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 133<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/14/02 4:21 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm24.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=93>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: religion of science</span><hr size=1> This entire thread is moot. Anyone of any intelligence knows that the answer to the question of the meaning of life is 42.<br>
